        <!-- 3 · THESIS -->
        <section id="thesis" class="memo-section" data-memo-section>
          <h2 class="display display--md">I. The Thesis</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>The Category.</strong> Global Gold is building the Global
            Gold Standard — global market infrastructure for allocated gold. The
            shared protocol, rulebook, and infrastructure layer for eligibility,
            collateral, liquidity, clearing, settlement, and governance. The
            right analogies are LBMA, DTCC, CLS, and SWIFT — in an asset class
            where no equivalent exists.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>The Size of the Prize.</strong> New York, London, Shanghai,
            and Dubai are each multi-billion-dollar-a-day gold markets — and each
            is boxed in twice over. A hub can only trade the metal held in its
            own regional vaults, and only during its own trading hours. No single
            one sees the world's gold, and no two are ever fully open at once.
            Tokenize allocated bars from every jurisdiction and place them on one
            always-on exchange, and those walls fall away. What emerges is not a
            fifth regional hub competing with the other four — it is the first
            genuinely global gold market: aggregating liquidity no single venue
            can reach, trading around the clock, and structurally positioned to
            dwarf the regional markets it unifies. That is the upside this round
            underwrites.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>The Problem, Concretely.</strong> The institutional gold
            market is an archipelago. LBMA-accredited vaults clear into London
            markets. COMEX-approved vaults clear into COMEX. SGE members clear into SGE.
            None of these hubs interoperates at the settlement layer — and in
            March 2020, the market showed what that costs. COMEX gold futures
            traded at sustained premiums of ~$70/oz over LBMA spot for three
            days, between hubs holding metal from the same refineries, because
            the physical re-casting chain between them broke. The CME had to
            amend its own delivery rules in real time. Clearing-pathway friction
            — not bar quality — is the dominant pricing variable in institutional
            gold.
          </p>
          <p>
            The dislocation is not history. Through December 2025 and January
            2026, silver repeated the pattern at larger scale: Shanghai physical
            traded roughly $10/oz over the COMEX settlement,¹ Indian retail rose
            21% in two weeks on delivery delays, and physical silver in Tokyo and
            the UAE changed hands at $120–130/oz against a COMEX print in the low
            $70s — regional markets walking away from the paper benchmark because
            no clearing pathway connects them. The introduced SILVER Act (H.R.
            8007 / S. 4621) expressly seeks greater geographic diversity,
            liquidity, market access, competition, and resilience in
            precious-metals depositories—federal recognition of the same
            market-structure problem Global Gold is built to solve.
          </p>
          <p>
            Outside the hubs entirely sits the wedge — state depositories, SPDIs,
            private depositories, refiner inventories: 40–80 facilities that
            matter, holding real metal with <strong>no</strong> pathway into
            global liquidity. Their only route today is to ship the bar and
            re-assay it into someone else's chain of custody.
          </p>
          <p><strong>The Mechanism.</strong> Our architecture is a two-way door between allocation and liquidity:</p>
          <ol class="memo-list memo-list--numbered">
            <li>
              <strong>The Bar.</strong> A specific, identifiable bar, allocated
              in a participating vault's on-chain Title Register — the vault's
              authoritative book of record. The vault is the registrar; title
              stays home.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The Claim.</strong> A Conditional Claim Token (CCT) — an
              on-chain claim to that exact bar, and the right to request its title
              transfer. One bar, one claim. The CCT is not itself title or a
              warehouse receipt; title remains in the vault's authoritative records.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The Unit.</strong> Collateralize the claim to mint Standard
              Metal Units — 1 SMU = 1 troy ounce of fine gold, backed 1:1 by
              locked claims on specific bars held by a bankruptcy-remote
              collateral agent and tradable on a continuous global market. U.S.
              Gold (USG) is the first jurisdiction-specific SMU and the flagship
              token: U.S.-vaulted gold made fungible, transferable, and liquid.
              As new jurisdictions join, each can issue its own SMU — UK gold,
              Swiss gold, Singapore gold — creating the foreign-exchange market of
              gold: one ounce, many jurisdictions, continuously priced against
              each other. Burn the units at any time to reclaim a claim on a
              comparable bar.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The Reserve &amp; Global Gold Token (gGold).</strong> If
              SMUs create the foreign-exchange market of gold, gGold becomes its
              reserve currency. A fixed basket of approved gold tokens — the
              protocol's own SMUs alongside leading issuers' units, spread across
              independent issuers and jurisdictions — is held in the Reserve and
              minted into gGold: one neutral gold unit, backed one-for-one in real
              ounces and redeemable by anyone for a pro-rata share of the basket.
              Local gold becomes global settlement money.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            <strong>Why gGold Matters.</strong> A market with USG, future
            jurisdictional SMUs, PAXG, XAUT, and other approved gold tokens needs
            a denominator. Without one, liquidity fragments into dozens of thin
            local pairs. gGold is that denominator: a reserve-backed unit that
            lets every gold trade through one neutral asset instead of routing
            through dollars or relying on a single issuer. The Reserve makes the
            neutrality credible — backing diversified across approved gold tokens,
            issuers, and jurisdictions; mint and redeem by rule; no single company
            able to freeze, gate, or break the unit. For users, gGold is gold that
            can move anywhere. For the network, it is the settlement asset that
            concentrates liquidity, routes volume, and turns local gold markets
            into one global market.
          </p>
          <blockquote class="memo-quote">
            <strong>Your bar never leaves the vault. The market never closes.</strong>
          </blockquote>
          <p>
            <strong>Why the Position Is Defensible.</strong> Four pillars, each
            architectural: every unit backed by a specific bar (<em>The Allocated
            Standard</em>); the vault keeps title and its customer relationships
            (<em>Title Stays Home</em>); no single company, issuer, or state can
            end the protocol (<em>Neutral by Construction</em>); units from any
            participating vault trade as one market (<em>One Standard, Every
            Vault</em>). PAXG cannot become this without ceasing to be a Paxos
            product. The incumbent hubs cannot become this without dissolving
            their regional charters. The position is not defended by secrecy — it
            is defended by what our competitors would have to stop being.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- 4 · WHY NOW -->
        <section id="why-now" class="memo-section" data-memo-section>
          <h2 class="display display--md">II. Why Now</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Gold Has Returned to the Center of the Global Reserve
            System.</strong> At market value, gold represented 27% of official
            reserves at year-end 2025—surpassing U.S. Treasuries at 22% and the
            euro at 15%, according to the European Central Bank. Central banks
            accumulated an average of approximately 1,000 tonnes annually over the
            last four years, roughly double the preceding decade's pace. In the
            World Gold Council's 2026 survey, 89% of reserve managers expect global
            official gold holdings to increase and a record 45% plan to increase
            their own institution's holdings.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Investment Demand and Liquidity Are Breaking Records.</strong>
            Total gold demand exceeded 5,000 tonnes and $555B for the first time in
            2025. Gold ETFs absorbed a record $89B of inflows, and global gold
            trading liquidity reached approximately $361B per day—up 56% year over
            year. The market is already global in demand and scale; its custody
            and settlement infrastructure is not.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Gold Is Becoming More Sovereign, More Distributed, and Harder
            to Connect.</strong> Reserve managers are increasing domestic storage
            and diversifying overseas vault locations as geopolitical risk
            reshapes custody strategy. Domestic gold-purchase programs are
            expanding across emerging markets, and Singapore is preparing
            central-bank gold-vaulting services as part of its effort to become a
            larger gold hub. The more distributed custody becomes, the more
            valuable a neutral standard becomes.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>The Technology and Legal Rails Are Finally Ready.</strong>
            Vault-controlled title registries, programmable collateral, real-time
            proof of reserves, cross-chain messaging, and continuous on-chain
            liquidity can now be assembled into institutional market
            infrastructure. Wyoming's DUNA framework supplies legal personality
            for decentralized standards governance; the GENIUS Act and March 2026
            SEC/CFTC interpretation provide clearer digital-asset categories; and
            allocated gold receives a 0% risk weight under applicable
            Basel-derived credit-risk rules.
          </p>
          <p>
            For the first time, reserve demand, record market liquidity,
            distributed custody, programmable settlement, and a clearer legal
            framework are converging at once. The market has the gold. Global Gold
            is building the system that connects it.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- 5 · BUSINESS MODEL -->
        <section id="business-model" class="memo-section" data-memo-section>
