        <!-- COMPLIANCE ARCHITECTURE -->
        <section id="regulatory" class="memo-section" data-memo-section>
          <h2 class="display display--md">IX. Compliance by Architecture</h2>
          <p>
            Global Gold was designed from the legal perimeter inward. The system
            separates each regulated function so no single entity acts as vault,
            issuer, protocol operator, standards body, treasury, and commercial
            software provider at once.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Vault-Controlled Custody, Title, and Issuance.</strong>
            Participating vaults custody the metal, operate their own Title
            Registers, maintain the authoritative ownership records, perform
            customer due diligence, and issue CCTs using licensed software. A CCT
            represents the right to request title transfer of a specific bar;
            title remains in the vault's records and moves only under the vault's
            Guardian-authorized policy.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Fully Reserved Settlement Instruments.</strong> Approved CCTs
            can be locked 1:1 to mint jurisdictional SMUs such as USG. The smart
            contracts verify the Approved Counterparty Registry on every
            collateralization event. gGold is minted only when a user delivers
            the required basket of approved gold tokens into the Reserve and is
            redeemable for a pro-rata share of that basket. The architecture uses
            no debt, leverage, discretionary collateral management, or liquidation
            engine.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Non-Custodial Technology Company.</strong> Global Gold OpCo
            licenses the Title Register and CCT Tokenization Engine to vaults,
            provides implementation and maintenance services, and may operate an
            optional, bypassable frontend. It does not custody gold, issue CCTs or
            SMUs, control customer title, or hold user assets in transit.
          </p>
          <p>
            Where fees settle on-chain, the transaction splits value atomically
            among the vault, OpCo technology-service slice, and Foundation Treasury
            without an intermediary taking custody. OpCo earns vault-paid B2B
            technology fees, optional frontend fees, and contracted services—the
            operating profile of a software provider rather than a money
            transmitter or virtual-currency administrator.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Independent Standards and Admissions.</strong> The Global Gold
            Council, a Wyoming DUNA, sets the protocol standards and fee schedule.
            The Foundation applies those standards to counterparty admissions,
            maintains the Approved Counterparty Registry, and operates the
            Foundation Treasury. The result is infrastructure designed for
            compliant institutional adoption: vault-controlled title, verified
            counterparties, fully reserved instruments, transparent collateral,
            non-custodial settlement, and clear separation between protocol
            governance and commercial technology.
          </p>
        </section>

